### 3.3 Player Runtime Logic

```ts
class Runtime {
  private currentSceneId: string
  private variables: Map<string, string> = new Map()
  private sceneGraph: SceneGraph
  
  // Load a scene into the iframe
  async loadScene(sceneId: string) {
    const scene = this.getScene(sceneId);
    this.currentSceneId = sceneId;
    await this.renderer.loadScene(scene);
    this.setupInteractions(scene.interactions);
    this.startPlayhead(scene.duration);
  }
  
  // Called when a scene's duration ends (for 'auto' edges)
  onSceneEnd() {
    const nextEdge = this.sceneGraph.edges.find(e => 
      e.fromSceneId === this.currentSceneId && 
      e.condition.type === 'auto'
    );
    if (nextEdge) this.loadScene(nextEdge.toSceneId);
    else this.emit('completed');
  }
  
  // Called when an interaction fires
  onInteractionFired(interactionId: string, value?: string) {
    const edge = this.sceneGraph.edges.find(e =>
      e.fromSceneId === this.currentSceneId &&
      e.condition.interactionId === interactionId
    );
    if (edge) this.loadScene(edge.toSceneId);
  }
  
  // Variable branching
  resolveEdge(fromSceneId: string): SceneEdge | null {
    const edges = this.sceneGraph.edges
      .filter(e => e.fromSceneId === fromSceneId);
    
    // Check variable conditions first
    for (const edge of edges) {
      if (edge.condition.type === 'variable') {
        const val = this.variables.get(edge.condition.variableName!);
        if (val === edge.condition.variableValue) return edge;
      }
    }
    // Fall back to auto
    return edges.find(e => e.condition.type === 'auto') ?? null;
  }
}
```

### 3.4 Interaction Renderers (in player)

The player renders interaction elements as absolutely-positioned 
divs overlaid on the scene iframe. These are NOT part of the scene 
HTML — they live in the player's overlay layer. This separation means:
- Interaction elements work the same in both mp4 and interactive mode
- MP4 export can optionally "bake in" static versions of interactions
  as SVG overlays (for a non-interactive preview feel)

**Hotspot renderer:**
```ts
function renderHotspot(el: HotspotElement, onClick: () => void) {
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.style.cssText = `
    position: absolute;
    left: ${el.x}%; top: ${el.y}%;
    width: ${el.width}%; height: ${el.height}%;
    cursor: pointer;
    border-radius: ${el.shape === 'circle' ? '50%' : '8px'};
    background: ${el.color}33;
    border: 2px solid ${el.color};
    display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
  `;
  if (el.style === 'pulse') {
    div.style.animation = 'inkframe-pulse 2s infinite';
  }
  if (el.label) {
    const label = document.createElement('span');
    label.textContent = el.label;
    label.style.cssText = 'color:white;font-size:14px;font-weight:600;';
    div.appendChild(label);
  }
  div.addEventListener('click', onClick);
  return div;
}
```

Add CSS keyframes for pulse, glow animations into the player's 
injected stylesheet.

**Choice renderer:**
Renders a centered overlay panel with:
- Optional question text above
- Row/column/grid of styled buttons
- Each button click fires onInteractionFired(optionId)
- Buttons use brandColor for the selected/hover state

**Quiz renderer:**
- Question text
- Option buttons (A, B, C, D style)
- On click: highlight correct (green) / wrong (red)
- Show explanation text if provided
- After 1.5s: fire appropriate edge

**Gate renderer:**
- Pauses the scene playhead when appearsAt is reached
- Shows a centered button with label
- On click: resumes and fires auto edge

**Tooltip renderer:**
- Renders a small pulsing indicator at trigger position
- On hover: shows a styled tooltip card with title + body
- Pure CSS hover, no JS needed

**Form renderer:**
- Centered overlay with form fields
- On submit: sets variables, fires jumpsToSceneId edge
- Variable values available in subsequent scenes

### 3.5 Variable Interpolation in Scenes

Scenes can reference variables using {varName} tokens.
Before loading a scene into the iframe, the player fetches 
the scene HTML, replaces all {varName} tokens with current 
variable values, then sets the iframe's srcdoc:

```ts
async loadScene(scene: PublishedScene) {
  let html = await fetch(scene.htmlUrl).then(r => r.text());
  
  // Replace variable tokens
  for (const [name, value] of this.variables) {
    html = html.replaceAll(`{${name}}`, value);
  }
  
  this.iframe.srcdoc = html;
}
```

Claude should be aware of this when generating scene content —
if the scene has variables defined, it can use {VarName} tokens
in SVG text elements, D3 titles, Three.js text sprites, etc.

