## IMPORTANT NOTES

1. The player iframe loads scene HTML via srcdoc for variable 
   interpolation. This means scenes cannot use relative asset 
   paths — all assets must use absolute URLs or data URIs. 
   Update writeSceneHTML to use absolute URLs for all src/href attrs.

2. The scene graph in MP4 mode: all edges are type "auto" and 
   the export just follows scenes in list order. No changes to 
   WVC pipeline.

3. Cross-origin iframe: the /v/[projectId] viewer and the 
   scene HTML files must be on the same origin OR scenes must 
   use srcdoc. Simplest: serve everything from same Next.js app.

4. Player CSS: inject a <style> tag into the player's shadow DOM 
   or into the document head with a namespaced prefix (inkframe-*)
   to avoid conflicts with the host page's CSS.

5. Password protection: store a bcrypt hash in the manifest. 
   The /v/[projectId] page checks for a cookie; if missing, shows 
   a password prompt before loading the manifest fully.

6. Analytics privacy: add a banner to published projects 
   "This presentation collects anonymous viewing data" 
   and a way for publishers to disable analytics per-project.

7. The player package should work with zero dependencies — 
   pure vanilla JS/TS, no React, no build requirements for 
   the end client. They just drop in a <script> tag.

8. For React Flow (scene graph): use the controlled mode with 
   nodes and edges stored in Zustand. Sync changes back to 
   sceneGraph in project state.

9. Variable tokens in Three.js scenes: Claude should use 
   CanvasTexture text sprites. In D3 scenes: use d3.select 
   title/label elements. Variables are replaced before the 
   HTML is loaded so they work in all scene types.

10. "Update" republishing: copy only changed scene files 
    (compare hash of HTML content). Don't re-copy unchanged 
    scenes to save time on large projects.
